commit accb153e6706f16ed6d596b82a569c97baf11434
Author: Marcelo Tosatti <mtosatti@redhat.com>

slub: apply new queue_percpu_work_on() interface

This commit updates slub to use the new qpw_{un,}lock*() and
queue_percpu_work_on() interface. It replaces local_{un,}lock*() and
schedule_work_on() with their queue percpu work equivalents to improve
performance and latency.

> diff --git a/mm/slub.c b/mm/slub.c
> index 2b2d33cc735c..e21dbf0fcad1 100644
> --- a/mm/slub.c
> +++ b/mm/slub.c
> @@ -2878,7 +2877,7 @@ static unsigned int __sheaf_flush_main_batch(struct kmem_cache *s)
>  
>  	remaining = sheaf->size;
>  
> -	local_unlock(&s->cpu_sheaves->lock);
> +	qpw_unlock(&s->cpu_sheaves->lock, cpu);
>  
>  	__kmem_cache_free_bulk(s, batch, &objects[0]);
>  
[ ... ]
> @@ -2908,11 +2907,13 @@ static bool sheaf_try_flush_main(struct kmem_cache *s)
>  	bool ret = false;
>  
>  	do {
> -		if (!local_trylock(&s->cpu_sheaves->lock))
> +		if (!local_qpw_trylock(&s->cpu_sheaves->lock))
>  			return ret;
>  
>  		ret = true;
> -		remaining = __sheaf_flush_main_batch(s);
> +
> +		qpw_lockdep_assert_held(&s->cpu_sheaves->lock);
> +		remaining = __sheaf_flush_main_batch(s, smp_processor_id());
>  
>  	} while (remaining);

Does this sequence leave the preemption or migration disable count
unbalanced?

In sheaf_try_flush_main(), the lock is acquired using
local_qpw_trylock(). When the new qpw macros are enabled, this explicitly
disables preemption/migration.

However, the lock is then released inside __sheaf_flush_main_batch() using
qpw_unlock(), which maps to spin_unlock(). Because it does not re-enable
preemption or migration like local_qpw_unlock() would, could this
permanently leave the task in an un-preemptible state on every successful
iteration of the loop?

[ ... ]
> @@ -3963,13 +3964,13 @@ static void flush_cpu_sheaves(struct work_struct *w)
>  {
>  	struct kmem_cache *s;
>  	struct slub_flush_work *sfw;
> +	int cpu = qpw_get_cpu(w);
>  
> -	sfw = container_of(w, struct slub_flush_work, work);
> -
> +	sfw = &per_cpu(slub_flush, cpu);
>  	s = sfw->s;
[ ... ]
> @@ -4015,17 +4016,18 @@ static void flush_rcu_sheaf(struct work_struct *w)
>  	struct slab_sheaf *rcu_free;
>  	struct slub_flush_work *sfw;
>  	struct kmem_cache *s;
> +	int cpu = qpw_get_cpu(w);
>  
> -	sfw = container_of(w, struct slub_flush_work, work);
> +	sfw = &per_cpu(slub_flush, cpu);
>  	s = sfw->s;

Does this code fetch the wrong CPU's sheaves if the work item migrates
during CPU hotplug?

Previously, using container_of() robustly recovered the original CPU's
slub_flush context even if the work migrated to a different CPU.

With the new changes, on kernels compiled without CONFIG_QPW,
qpw_get_cpu() expands directly to smp_processor_id(). If a target CPU goes
offline while its work item is pending, the workqueue subsystem migrates
it to an unbound worker pool running on a different executing CPU.

When the work finally executes, smp_processor_id() will return the
executing CPU rather than the original target CPU. Can this cause the
worker to incorrectly access the executing CPU's slub_flush state,
potentially leaving the actual target CPU's sheaves unflushed and causing
a memory leak?

