Okay, I've got something here. I was looking at `flush_all_cpus_locked`, and it seems straightforward, right? We iterate through online CPUs, queue work using `queue_percpu_work_on`, and then flush it. If we use `qpw_get_cpu(w)` which returns `smp_processor_id()` on non-CONFIG_QPW builds, it works because the work executes on the intended CPU. I was satisfied, but then it hit me. What happens if the `queue_work_on` call *fails* for some reason, for example, if the target CPU is going down? But wait, we have `lockdep_assert_cpus_held()`, which implies CPU hotplug is locked. So, it *can't* go down. `queue_work_on` for an online CPU will run on that CPU, so `smp_processor_id()` is safe because CPU hotplug is locked. Problem solved, or so I thought...

Then, I shifted my focus to `flush_rcu_sheaves_on_cache`. I saw the same pattern, but something immediately jumped out at me: There's no `lockdep_assert_cpus_held()` in this function! That's a red flag. If it doesn't hold that lock, a CPU *can* go offline while work is queued or executing. That means `queue_work_on()` could send the work to the unbound workqueue. This work can then be executed on a *different* CPU! And if this happens, and `flush_rcu_sheaf` uses `smp_processor_id()`, it will return the wrong CPU! We'd be flushing the sheaves of the wrong CPU, and using the wrong per-cpu variables. This is a subtle but significant race condition.

I had to verify this... because it is really dangerous. `flushwq` is a standard workqueue, which will likely handle CPU hotplug through either an unbound or bound setup. So if a CPU goes offline, its work items might be rescued or migrated. If the work is migrated, `qpw_get_cpu(w)`, which is `smp_processor_id()` without `CONFIG_QPW`, will definitely give the wrong CPU! Now I need to go back and check the code, and confirm this issue is what I think it is, then identify any mitigation strategies, or further areas that this pattern is used in the SLUB cache flushing.


